<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Originally described from Japan as a leaf miner in the ornamental daylily 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Hemerocallis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hemerocallis fulva subsp. kwanso" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fulva" subSpecies="kwanso">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hemerocallis fulva kwanso</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this fly is a recent invasive in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, GL" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the North American Prairie Conference" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B292" refString="Williams, GL, Steck, GJ, 2011. New invasive daylily leafminer, Ophiomyia kwansonis Sasakawa, identified in North America. First Detector Network News 6(9): 7-8. Southern Plant Diagnostic Network (SPDN), University of Florida." title="New invasive daylily leafminer, Ophiomyia kwansonis Sasakawa, identified in North America. First Detector Network News 6 (9): 7 - 8. Southern Plant Diagnostic Network (SPDN), University of Florida." year="2011">Williams and Steck 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4289/0013-8797.116.4.421" author="Williams, GL" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the North American Prairie Conference" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B293" refString="Williams, GL, Steck, GJ, 2014. Ophiomyia kwansonis Sasakawa (Diptera: Agromyzidae), the Daylily Leafminer, an Asian Species Recently Identified in the Continental United States. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 116(4): 421-428. https://doi.org/10.4289/0013-8797.116.4.421" title="Ophiomyia kwansonis Sasakawa (Diptera: Agromyzidae), the Daylily Leafminer, an Asian Species Recently Identified in the Continental United States. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 116 (4): 421 - 428." url="https://doi.org/10.4289/0013-8797.116.4.421" year="2014">2014</bibRefCitation>
), and will soon likely occur in most regions where daylily is grown. Life history and immature stages are discussed in 
<bibRefCitation author="Sasakawa, M" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="307 - 472" refId="B210" refString="Sasakawa, M, 1961. A study of the Japanese Agromyzidae (Diptera), Part 2. Pacific Insects 3: 307 - 472" title="A study of the Japanese Agromyzidae (Diptera), Part 2." volume="3" year="1961">Sasakawa (1961)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, GL" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the North American Prairie Conference" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B292" refString="Williams, GL, Steck, GJ, 2011. New invasive daylily leafminer, Ophiomyia kwansonis Sasakawa, identified in North America. First Detector Network News 6(9): 7-8. Southern Plant Diagnostic Network (SPDN), University of Florida." title="New invasive daylily leafminer, Ophiomyia kwansonis Sasakawa, identified in North America. First Detector Network News 6 (9): 7 - 8. Southern Plant Diagnostic Network (SPDN), University of Florida." year="2011">Williams and Steck (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. The only other agromyzid known to occur on 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Hemerocallis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hemerocallis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Hemerocallis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Iwasaki" authorityYear="1993" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza hemerocallis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hemerocallis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza hemerocallis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Iwasaki, also from Japan, but this species feeds on seeds, not within leaves (
<bibRefCitation author="Iwasaki, A" journalOrPublisher="Japanese Journal of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="303 - 306" refId="B121" refString="Iwasaki, A, 1993. A new seed-feeding species of Liriomyza (Diptera, Agromyzidae) from Japan. Japanese Journal of Entomology 61 (2): 303 - 306" title="A new seed-feeding species of Liriomyza (Diptera, Agromyzidae) from Japan." volume="61" year="1993">Iwasaki 1993</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
